3.0  Executive Summary				

Pryor Chemical Company (PCC) and its management staff are committed to operating and maintaining all of its processes in a safe and responsible manner.  The facility uses a combination of accidental release prevention programs and emergency response planning programs to help ensure the safety of its employees and the public, as well as protection of the environment.  It is a facility policy to implement appropriate controls to prevent releases of regulated substances where possible.  This document provides a brief overview of the comprehensive risk management activities that have been designed and implemented, including the following:

¿	A description of the facility and use of substances exceeding threshold quantities, in a single process, which are regulated by the EPA's RMP Rule;
¿	A summary of the potential off-site consequences from possible accidental chemical releases;
¿	An overview of accidental release prevention programs;
¿	A five-year accident history for accidental releases of chemicals regulated by the RMP Rule;
¿	An overview of the Emergency Response Program; and,
¿	An overview of planned improvements at the facility to help prevent accidental chemical releases from occurring and adversely affecting employees, the public, and the environment.

3.1  Regulated Substances

	PCC manufactures nitrogenous fertilizer.  The facility consists of an anhydrous ammonia plant, two nitric acid plants, two liquid ammonium nitrate plants, a CO2 plant, and two liquid urea plants.  Anhydrous ammonia (ammonia) is produced from processing natural gas, and chlorine is used as a disinfectant in the facility's cooling towers. Ammonia and chlorine are the only substances at the facility that are listed on the RMP Rule Toxic Substances list and stored or maintained above threshold quantities, causing them to be subject to the requirements of 40 CFR Part 68.  The nitric acid produced at the facility is less than 80% concentration; theref
